---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';


export const meta = {
  title: 'Food Photography Tips for Beginners',
  description: 'A complete beginner',
  category: 'guide',
};

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Food Photography Tips for Beginners",
    "description": "A complete beginner's guide to phone food photography. Learn about natural lighting, camera angles, composition rules, styling props, and top editing apps to capture mouth-watering photos.",
    "url": "https://28grams.vip/food-photography-tips",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "28grams"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the best lighting for food photography?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Natural window light is the best. Avoid direct sunlight as it creates harsh shadows; instead, use diffused, indirect sunlight. Never use your phone's flash."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How can I improve my phone food photography composition?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Use the rule of thirds by turning on your phone's camera grid. Place the main subject at the intersections of the grid lines rather than dead center, and leave some negative space."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Which angle should I use when taking photos of food?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The angle depends on the dish. Use a 45-degree angle for most plated dishes, an overhead (flat lay) angle for bowls or tablescapes, and an eye-level angle for tall foods like burgers or stacked pancakes."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the best apps for editing food photos?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Lightroom Mobile is excellent for adjusting colors and lighting. Snapseed offers powerful selective editing tools, and VSCO provides beautiful, film-like preset filters."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How can I take good food photos in a dark restaurant?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Ask a friend to use their phone's flashlight and bounce the light off a white napkin or menu toward the food. This creates a softer light than a direct flash. Also, use your camera's night mode if available."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];

const mainEntityArray = schema[1].mainEntity;
---

<SiteLayout
  site="28grams"
  title="Food Photography Tips for Beginners"
  description="A complete beginner's guide to phone food photography. Learn about natural lighting, camera angles, composition rules, styling props, and top editing apps to capture mouth-watering photos."
  canonical="https://28grams.vip/food-photography-tips"
  schema={JSON.stringify(schema)}
>
  <style>
* { margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; }
.page-wrapper {
  font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
  background: #0a060a;
  color: #e0d0d8;
  min-height: 100vh;
  --card-bg: #120c10;
  --border-color: #2a1820;
  --accent-color: #C2185B;
  --text-secondary: #888;
}

code, .mono { font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; }

.hero { text-align: center; padding: 48px 24px 24px; background: linear-gradient(180deg, #1a0a14 0%, #0a060a 100%); }
.hero h1 { font-size: 2.4rem; font-weight: 900; color: #fff; margin-bottom: 6px; }
.hero h1 span { background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--accent-color), #ff6b9d); -webkit-background-clip: text; -webkit-text-fill-color: transparent; background-clip: text; }
.hero p { color: #666; font-size: 0.95rem; max-width: 560px; margin: 0 auto; }
.main { max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 32px 20px 40px; }

/* Formula Card */
.formula-card, .guide-card {
  background: var(--card-bg);
  border: 2px solid var(--border-color);
  border-radius: 16px;
  overflow: hidden;
  margin-bottom: 32px;
}
.card-header {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
  padding: 16px 20px;
  background: #150d12;
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
}
.card-header h2 { font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 700; color: #fff; margin: 0; }
.card-content { padding: 20px; }
.card-content p { color: #c8b8c0; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 12px; }
.card-content ul { padding-left: 20px; margin-bottom: 12px; color: #c8b8c0; line-height: 1.6; }
.card-content li { margin-bottom: 6px; }

/* SEO content */
.content h2 { font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 800; color: #fff; margin: 40px 0 14px; }
.content h3 { font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #ddd; margin: 24px 0 10px; }
.content p { font-size: 0.9rem; color: #777; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 14px; }

/* Recipe Details */
.recipe-section { margin-bottom: 40px; padding-bottom: 24px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
.recipe-section:last-of-type { border-bottom: none; }
.recipe-header { display: flex; align-items: baseline; gap: 12px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
.recipe-header h3 { margin: 0; font-size: 1.3rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
.recipe-meta { font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-secondary); background: #1a1015; padding: 4px 8px; border-radius: 4px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }

.recipe-info-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr));
    gap: 16px;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
}
.recipe-info-card {
    background: #150d12;
    padding: 12px 16px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
}
.recipe-info-label {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-bottom: 4px;
}
.recipe-info-value {
    color: #e0d0d8;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.4;
}

/* FAQ */
.faq-list { margin-top: 24px; }
.faq-item { margin-bottom: 24px; }
.faq-q { font-weight: 700; color: #fff; margin-bottom: 8px; font-size: 1.05rem; }
.faq-a { color: #777; font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; }

@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .hero h1 { font-size: 1.8rem; }
  .recipe-header { flex-direction: column; gap: 4px; }
}
  </style>

<div class="page-wrapper">
<div class="hero">
  <h1>Food Photography <span>Tips</span> 📸</h1>
  <p>Your complete guide to phone food photography. Learn about lighting, angles, composition, and editing to capture stunning, mouth-watering photos.</p>
</div>

<div class="main">

  <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 800; color: #fff; margin: 40px 0 20px;">Lighting Fundamentals</h2>

  <div class="recipe-section">
    <div class="recipe-header">
      <h3>Natural Lighting</h3>
      <span class="recipe-meta">Core Principle</span>
    </div>
    <div class="recipe-info-grid">
        <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">Window Light</div><div class="recipe-info-value">Always shoot near a large window. Indirect, soft daylight is the most flattering light for food.</div></div>
        <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">Diffusers</div><div class="recipe-info-value">If direct sunlight hits the food, hang a sheer white curtain to soften the harsh shadows.</div></div>
        <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">Reflectors</div><div class="recipe-info-value">Use a piece of white foam board opposite the window to bounce light back onto the shadowed side.</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 800; color: #fff; margin: 40px 0 20px;">Finding the Right Angle</h2>

  <div class="recipe-section">
    <div class="recipe-header">
      <h3>Angles</h3>
      <span class="recipe-meta">Perspective</span>
    </div>
    <div class="recipe-info-grid">
        <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">45-Degree Angle</div><div class="recipe-info-value">The most common angle. Mimics how we naturally see food when sitting at a table. Great for plated meals.</div></div>
        <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">Overhead (Flat Lay)</div><div class="recipe-info-value">Shooting from directly above (90 degrees). Perfect for bowls, smoothie bowls, pizza, and showing the entire table layout.</div></div>
        <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">Eye-Level (0-Degrees)</div><div class="recipe-info-value">Shooting straight on from the side. Ideal for showcasing height and layers, like stacked burgers, sandwiches, or pancakes.</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 800; color: #fff; margin: 40px 0 20px;">Mastering Composition</h2>

  <div class="recipe-section">
    <div class="recipe-header">
      <h3>Composition Rules</h3>
      <span class="recipe-meta">Structure</span>
    </div>
    <div class="recipe-info-grid">
        <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">Rule of Thirds</div><div class="recipe-info-value">Turn on your camera grid. Place the most important part of the dish at the intersections of the grid lines.</div></div>
        <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">Negative Space</div><div class="recipe-info-value">Leave empty areas in the frame. This draws the viewer's eye directly to the food and provides balance.</div></div>
        <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">Color Theory</div><div class="recipe-info-value">Use contrasting colors to make food pop. For example, a red tomato soup on a blue background or adding green herbs to a brown stew.</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 800; color: #fff; margin: 40px 0 20px;">Elevating the Scene</h2>

  <div class="formula-card">
    <div class="card-header">
      <h2>Styling Props</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="card-content">
      <p>Props tell a story and add texture without distracting from the main dish.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Surfaces & Boards:</strong> Wooden cutting boards add warmth, while marble slabs create a clean, modern aesthetic.</li>
        <li><strong>Linens & Napkins:</strong> Wrinkled linen napkins introduce organic texture. Stick to neutral or muted colors.</li>
        <li><strong>Utensils & Ingredients:</strong> Scatter raw ingredients used in the dish (e.g., a dusting of flour, a few whole coffee beans) or include vintage silverware for character.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="formula-card">
    <div class="card-header">
      <h2>Editing Apps</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="card-content">
      <p>Post-processing is crucial for taking a good photo and making it great.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lightroom Mobile:</strong> The industry standard for color grading, adjusting white balance, and pulling detail from shadows.</li>
        <li><strong>Snapseed:</strong> Perfect for localized adjustments. Use the 'Selective' tool to brighten specific areas of the food without blowing out the background.</li>
        <li><strong>VSCO:</strong> Offers beautiful, film-emulation filters. Keep the intensity low (around 30-50%) to maintain the food's natural appetizing colors.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="formula-card">
    <div class="card-header">
      <h2>iPhone vs Android Camera Tips</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="card-content">
      <p>Know your device's strengths and weaknesses.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>iPhone:</strong> Tends to shoot slightly warmer with deeper contrast. Use Portrait mode for a shallow depth of field, but tap and hold to lock focus and exposure (AE/AF Lock).</li>
        <li><strong>Android:</strong> Often processes colors with higher saturation. If your phone has a 'Pro' mode, use it to manually adjust white balance to ensure whites look truly white, not yellow or blue.</li>
        <li><strong>Universal Tip:</strong> Always clean your camera lens with a microfiber cloth before shooting. Smudges create blurry, glowing photos.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="formula-card">
    <div class="card-header">
      <h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="card-content">
      <p>Watch out for these frequent beginner errors.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Using the Flash:</strong> Built-in flash creates harsh shadows and flattens the texture of the food. Never use it.</li>
        <li><strong>Cluttered Backgrounds:</strong> A messy table distracts the eye. Clear away dirty napkins, extraneous glasses, and distracting background elements.</li>
        <li><strong>Shooting Cold Food:</strong> Food looks best when it's freshly prepared. Melted cheese congeals and hot soups lose their steam quickly.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="formula-card">
    <div class="card-header">
      <h2>Restaurant Food Photo Etiquette</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="card-content">
      <p>How to get the shot without being "that person."</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Be Quick:</strong> Don't make your dining companions wait 10 minutes to eat their cooling food. Get your shot and put the phone away.</li>
        <li><strong>Be Discreet:</strong> Avoid standing on chairs or holding your phone high above neighboring tables.</li>
        <li><strong>No Flash in Dark Rooms:</strong> Never use a flash in a dimly lit, intimate restaurant. It's highly disruptive. Ask a friend to use their phone's flashlight, pointed at a white menu, to bounce a soft light onto the food instead.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>


  <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 800; color: #fff; margin: 40px 0 20px;">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    {mainEntityArray.map((faq) => (
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">{faq.name}</div>
        <div class="faq-a">{faq.acceptedAnswer.text}</div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>
</div>
</div>
</SiteLayout>
